The writers of the story want us to see Muhammad as a special person who didn't need to prove anything. But this makes me think they are taking away from Jesus' story.

The story has many examples of people converting to Islam. But some of these stories come from people who heard from others. This makes me not trust the stories as much. I think the writers want us to believe that these stories are true, but it makes me wonder if they are really true.

What bothers me most is that the story tries to make Muhammad seem like a perfect man. But history says he was not always kind and humble. I wonder if Muslims today know the real story of Muhammad's life.

The ideas of Jesus and his beliefs in his time were soon forgotten in the growth of Christian thought after his death.  If we look at this history, we see a big change in Christianity moving further and further from its start.  We can see a big change happening today.  Many people are becoming more aware and open to new ideas.  But the old way of thinking will not go away.  Some people will always want to follow the old rules.  They may not be enough to stop the change.  In the future, more people will understand the history of Christianity.  They will want to know what was really said by Jesus.  It will take time, maybe many years.  But it will happen.  There will be a big change in the history of Christianity.  It will go back to its start.  People will remove the ideas that were added over time.  It will be like going back in time.  They will find the true meaning of what Jesus said.  When this change happens in the United States and Europe, many people will follow Jesus' ideas again.  The church will still be strong, but it will be different.  There will be less difference between people who believe in Jesus.  They will be more alike.  This is like what happened in history before.  For example, the Roman Empire used to be against Christians, but later it became Christian.  Our country used to treat African-Americans unfairly, but now they have leaders.  This big change will happen in the Christian religion.  It will go back to its start and make things more alike.

If we look back far enough, we find that Christianity started from Judaism.  The core of the Jewish religion was one God, a divinely revealed God, and the Jewish holy books.  But the Jewish people did not all agree.  They had different groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and regular people.  They had different ideas about God.

I think The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish. They only think about themselves and want good things for themselves, but not others. The book shows this in many ways. One way is the owners and managers of large factories. They want to make their companies big and strong. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt because of their actions. According to Upton Sinclair, the book's writer, factories cause a lot of damage to the environment. The air is dirty and animals and people are hurt.

The owners and managers also did not care about their workers. They wanted to make money. They forced workers to work long hours and then fired many workers at the same time without helping them find new jobs. There were no laws to protect workers during that time. This meant the owners and managers could do what they wanted. They made workers work in bad conditions and live in poor neighborhoods. There were no organizations to help workers. Some groups that were supposed to help workers made money from them instead. Workers were treated very badly and had no way to escape their difficult lives. They were described as slaves because they had no control over their lives and were dependent on their bosses for everything.

The Jungle is a book about the problems in a place called Packingtown. It shows how people were treated unfairly. The book says that when people are treated very badly, they often act badly too. This is what happened in Packingtown. People were poor, hungry, and had no help. They did what they had to do to survive.

Many writers use different methods to make readers feel a certain way about important subjects. Some of these methods work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these methods in his novel The Great Gatsby. One method he uses is to pair an adjective with a noun in a way that is not usual. This makes readers think of a certain feeling or idea about the subject. 

Fitzgerald uses this method with many colors, including gold, green, white, and red. He gives meaning to these colors and then uses them to make readers remember a feeling about important objects. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald gives special meaning to the colors white and gray. He makes white mean something nice and higher class, and gray mean something old and worn out. 

At the beginning of the novel, Fitzgerald uses white and gray many times. Everyone in the story wears white, like Daisy and Jordan. Even Nick wears white clothes to Gatsby's party. But when he gets an idea about Gatsby's party, he describes the rooms as bright and colorful, not white. Fitzgerald uses white and gray on common things too, like buildings and people. He describes the lower part of New York as "white chasms." He also describes a person's name as a "gray name." 

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to describe ordinary people and places. He says Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood." He says the land in the valley of ashes is "gray." He describes a dog seller as an "old gray man." Fitzgerald uses these colors to show readers something first with Daisy. After a long time, he describes Daisy wearing white and gray things. This makes readers see her as not very special, but just something that Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald uses this method many times to make readers see Daisy as something ordinary. For example, he describes her fur as a "gray haze." He also says she wears a white dress before Tom and Gatsby meet. This makes readers think of Daisy as something Gatsby wants, but not very interesting.

San Diego County grows many crops. The climate is sunny and warm. It is good for growing food. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, and squash are some of the crops. Also, people grow peaches, lemons, berries, and peppers. Many people want to buy food from local farms that use organic methods. They use no chemicals to make their food. This makes a lot of demand for organic food in the San Diego area. 

Many people want to buy organic eggs and milk from local farms. Some farms also give tours. People can see how food is made. They can also walk in the woods and watch birds. This kind of farm can help the landowner get money from the government. It also helps the environment.

Organic farming is good for the environment. It helps many kinds of plants and animals. But it can be more expensive than other farming methods. It takes more work to remove weeds and pests. The farmer must also use natural ways to make the soil healthy. This can be expensive. A small farm is not as efficient as a big farm. It takes more work to make the same amount of food.

The land I chose is near a town called Potrero. It is in unincorporated San Diego County, California. The land is 160 acres. There are chaparral, grass, and oak trees. It is close to the Cleveland National Forest. Many kinds of plants and animals live in this area. Some are endangered. They need our help to survive. The area was home to Native Americans a long time ago. Later, people settled there and raised cows.

I looked at a website to find a real piece of land. I also looked at government programs to help small farmers. I found an organic farm in the same area. This farm uses natural methods to grow food. It helps the environment and makes money. I will use this farm as an example of what someone could do with this land.

Culture is important in any talk. A culture is not one thing. It is not the same everywhere or in one place. We should not say things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are friendly." These statements are too general. To understand a culture, we must know its value. A value is a reason for something.

When we meet a new culture, we compare it to our own culture. This helps us understand. But we must accept a culture as it is. We should not try to change it. 

Knowing a culture is not just about history or past events. It is also about what people believe and how they feel. When we go to a place where people have a different culture, we must respect their traditions. This helps us succeed in our talks.

A country's culture is not the only culture. A company can have its own culture too. For example, some companies work many hours. Other companies work fewer hours. We can see a company's culture in how people dress, how they talk, and what they do for their work. Some companies want employees to help charities. Other companies do not.

Understanding culture is important. It helps us know why people do things. For example, in some cultures, people want to save face. This means they do not want to lose respect. In other cultures, people value making a good deal. If we know these values, we can do better in our talks.

Before we talk, we should know some things about the person we are talking to. This helps us do a good job in our talks. But we must also know something about ourselves. This helps us understand the other person better.

The Bible says: "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This is found in Psalm 14. Two famous thinkers, St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas, discussed the existence of God. We will compare their ideas. We will assume both are correct about God for this discussion. This will help us compare their two ideas.

St. Anselm said we can know God exists by looking inside ourselves. He said we can't think of a time when God didn't exist. We know God exists because we know the truth inside our minds. This idea is called faith. Faith is trusting in something without proof.

Thomas Aquinas had a different idea. He said we can know God exists through reason and evidence. We don't need faith to believe. Aquinas gave five logical reasons for God's existence. These reasons are change, cause and effect, things that depend on others, degrees of good and bad, and order. He said these reasons show that God is necessary. It's like a puzzle: if you see all the other pieces, you can know what the missing piece looks like.

A long time ago, in the 5th or 6th century BCE, a prince was born. This prince later became known as the Buddha. During his life, he left the world and became a wise man. His teachings started a new religion, called Buddhism. The most traditional part of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is more than 2,500 years old. It is different now from when the Buddha was alive. We can see this in many places, for example in Sri Lanka, where people celebrate the 'water-cutting ceremony'. Monks and people who live in the community both participate in this ceremony. It has special meaning, even though the Buddha never taught about a holiday like this. The Theravada Buddhist community has to change its ideas over time. This happens because of internal and external forces. Internal forces come from inside the Buddhist group. External forces come from people who are not Buddhist. Some forces are good, some are bad. Some forces are friendly, some are not.

We need to know some special words. Internal means something that comes from inside the Buddhist group. External means something that comes from people who are not Buddhist. Hostile means something that harms or wants to harm the Buddhist group. Benign means something that does not want to hurt the Buddhist group, even if it might happen as a result. We will use these words many times in this discussion.

First, we need to learn the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Theravada Buddhists believe in three important things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes three baskets of texts. The first basket has all the teachings of the Buddha. The second basket has rules for behavior. The third basket has ideas about the universe. Some of these ideas are that there is no soul, life has suffering, and everything is changing. To stop suffering and death, people need to understand these ideas. When people are enlightened, they will stop suffering and also stop wanting things they do not have and hating others. The Buddha taught rules for living. For people who live in the community, there are five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not behave badly with others, and do not take alcohol. For monks, there are more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. First, life is suffering. Second, our desires cause suffering. Third, we can overcome suffering.

The United States and Mexico are two countries that had a long rivalry for 57 years. This lasted from 1836 to 1893. Their biggest fight was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. The United States won the war and got Texas and the Southwest from Mexico. This was not the only fight between the two countries. They had many other smaller fights, but they stopped before World War One. 

The rivalry started because of disagreements on important issues like religion, culture, and traditions. The two countries also had different economic interests. This is not unusual. Many countries that share a border have disagreements that lead to rivalries. The United States and Mexico are like many other countries that have had a long time of disagreements with a neighbor. 

David M. Pletcher said in 1977 that the United States has long-lasting problems with Mexico and Cuba. Both countries are close to the United States and have been rivals. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States. 

The United States and Mexico had disagreements because of their different religions. This is not a new problem. Many countries throughout history have had disagreements because of their religions. Sally Frahm said in 2001 that Americans used to be against Catholicism and monarchy. This was different from their opposition to fascism and communism in the 20th century. The disagreement between the United States and Mexico was similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union. However, their disagreements were not about politics, but about their different religions. The United States and Mexico did not trust each other because of the distrust between the English and Spanish. This made it difficult for the two countries to have good relations. 

Diehl and Goerts listed 17 fights between the United States and Mexico between 1836 and 1893. Most of these fights were about territory and border problems. Bandits and outlaws from American towns near the border were a big problem until the United States and Mexico used their armies to control the border. 

Schmitt said that the rivalry between the United States and Mexico started to end when Mexico needed the United States more. The United States then changed its goals from taking territory to helping Mexico's economy in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I got very sick. I was a nurse at the time. I became a nurse because I wanted a steady job. People always get sick, so I thought it would be easy to find work. But my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist.

Unfortunately, I am still sick today. I am 46 years old and have no money. I get help from the government, but it is not enough. Every day is hard for me. I am grateful for my family and friends who help me.

Life is unpredictable. Bad things can happen to anyone. No matter how strong you are, you need help sometimes. 

I agree that we should not rely too much on the government. But I think we should help each other instead of trying to do everything alone. We should trust and help our neighbors.

The idea of "rugged individualism" is not true. Our ancestors were able to survive hard times because they helped each other. They did not go through difficult times alone.

So, be prepared. Have a kit with food, water, and a first aid kit. But also get to know your neighbors. They can help you in an emergency.

If you have a farm, grow your own food. It is a good idea. But do not forget to help others too.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules that affect how they change? A long time ago, a scientist named D'Arcy Thompson said that it is hard to explain how living things are made using math. This is still true today.

Recently, scientists have used math to study how mollusks grow their shells. We are doing a study to see if using math to understand how mollusks grow can help us learn about how they change over time.

We used special pictures of mollusks to find numbers that can help us make math models of their shells. We put these numbers into a computer program to make math models of what the shells could look like. We used these models to see how shells can change.

A shell is like a tube that turns around in a circle. It turns 360 degrees in all directions. The turns are called whorls. They are like circles that go around a middle point. The middle point is called the columella.

The whorls can grow at different speeds. A line that divides each whorl is called a suture. The last whorl is usually the biggest. The other whorls are called the spire.

The top of the spire is called the apex. The other end is called the base. The animal comes out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways. We can look at the top, the bottom, the front, or the back. The front is the usual way to look at a shell.

To count the whorls, we look at the top of the shell and find where the first line is. We draw a line and count the whorls from there. We can count to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell is like a path that the animal follows as it grows. We can draw a map of the path using numbers. We can use math to change the map and see how the shell grows.

The number of babies and young children dying in Indonesia has not changed much over the last ten years.  The country is doing well in meeting some of the United Nations' goals, like improving water and sanitation.  However, the country is not improving fast enough in health care for children and mothers to meet its targets.

Indonesia has made some progress in getting more health workers at births.  Now, 72% of births have a skilled health worker.  But, these workers are not always doctors or nurses.  They are sometimes traditional workers like midwives.  These workers cannot give medical help if there are problems during pregnancy.  Many mothers die because of bleeding during childbirth.  The progress in this area is not as good as it seems.

Fewer children under five years old are treated for diarrhea by a health professional.  We do not have all the information about care after birth.  But we know that this is a problem.  The rates of care are low across the country.

Not enough women in Indonesia have a cesarean section, which is a medical operation to help the baby come out safely.  Only about 4% of women have cesarean sections.  The rate of cesarean sections is higher in cities, 7%, but lower in rural areas, 2%.  This shows that people in cities have better access to healthcare.  We also know that the poor have a hard time getting healthcare.  In fact, the poor get 27% fewer healthcare services than the rich.  This is because they have to pay out of their own money.

To improve the health care for babies and mothers, we need to find the best way to solve the problem.  One way is to focus on one area of health care at a time.  This can give us quick results.  But there are some problems with this approach.  It can take money away from other areas of health care.  It can also make it hard for people to work in other areas because there is not enough money.  Another problem is that when we have many programs working together, they can create too much paperwork and waste money.

Victorian stories are known for their careful details and focus on the rich people of the time.  Two stories that are not like this are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  These stories use mystery and strange events.  These things help us know the characters better and understand their feelings and ideas.

In one part of the story, Oliver Twist, Oliver's mind is full of confusing ideas. He is still thinking about two men, Sikes and Crackit, who are arguing. When he pays attention, he sees that he is talking to them. Then, there is a loud noise and he is moved away quickly. Oliver feels pain and is confused.

These stories use mystery in strange ways. In Oliver Twist, strange things happen and help us know about Oliver's feelings and the world around him. In one part, Oliver remembers a time when he was shot. He relives the memory like it was a dream. This shows that Oliver had no control over what happened to him. He was very sick and did not know what was happening. The pain was always there, and he was very afraid.

This event makes us wonder who caused Oliver's bad luck. It was not Oliver's fault, so he had no control over what happened. This event also shows that Oliver is giving up. He has lost hope and does not try to change his situation.

In another part of the story, the author writes: "The day was short. It was gone as soon as it came. The night was very quiet, but it did not last long."

I worked with students in an after-school program two years ago. I helped students with their schoolwork, but my best subjects were English and reading. One student, Adrian, had trouble reading. He was in third or fourth grade. I thought something was strange about his reading problems. Some letters he read well, others not. Adrian's family is from Latin America. He spoke very good English, but I thought he might have trouble with the alphabet.

I met his mother when she came to pick him up from the after-school program. She did not speak English. I helped some with communication, but then I realized Adrian knew how to read. He just did not know the English alphabet very well.

This story shows us a problem in schools, especially in California. Even if a student speaks good English, reading can still be hard. We need to find a solution. For Adrian, tutoring in English reading helped. But for other students, it is more complicated.

We need to use many things to help students who do not speak much English. Some ideas are dual language classes, regular classes, private tutors, and English as a Second Language (ESL) classes. We need to use all of these things together.

Dual language classes are a good idea. They help students who speak different languages. Children in these programs do better in school. Some people are afraid that these programs waste money and are not helpful. But that is not true. If we use these programs in all schools, all students will benefit.

We do not need all teachers to be bilingual. That is too hard. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages. They can assist teachers in the classroom.

When we are young, many people tell us that there is something bigger than us. This thing is hard to understand. We can learn about it in Sunday school or other places of worship. Some people believe in the religions their parents teach them. Others do not believe. They think there is no more than what we can see and touch.

A person's beliefs can change over time. This is because we grow and get new ideas. We try to find our own path in life. We want to understand the world and our place in it.

My father was sick for a long time. He had a disease that hurt him a lot. He got thinner and his hair fell out. One day, we sat on the porch together. It was raining hard. My father looked out into the rain. He looked sad. I was sad too. I did not want to talk about how much I would miss him. Talking about it would make it more painful.

We sat together, looking at the rain. I wanted to remember my father when he was happy, not when he was sick. I wanted to remember how he lived, not how he died. My father did not want me to see him die. He would not want me to be sad.

After my father died, I was very sad. I stayed in bed for three days. I waited for news from my family. But no one called me. I thought about God and why he would make my father suffer so much. I did not pray because I did not think God was listening.

The Gothic Novel is a mix of old and new things. It has both old ideas and new ways of writing. Many people do not like it or do not understand it. Some think it is not deep. Others say it is great because it makes us feel the 'terrible sublime' (a big feeling of fear and wonder).

The first Gothic Novel was called "The Castle of Otranto". It was written by Horace Walpole. He took ideas from old romances and new novels to make a new way of writing. He used old ideas and new ways to create a new style. 

The word "gothic" was used to describe many things before. People thought it was old-fashioned. But the Gothic Novel used these old ideas and made something new. It combined old and new in a way that made it popular for a long time.

One of the main ideas in Gothic Novels is chivalry. Chivalry is the idea of being a brave, honorable, and kind knight. In "The Castle of Otranto", this idea is used to show what a true knight should be like. The writer, Horace Walpole, wanted to show what was missing in society. He was unhappy with the state of the world and thought that people had lost the good qualities of the past.

In the novel, a character named Frederic is a good example of a chivalric person. He is a prince who has suffered and is brave. He has many qualities of a true knight. He is kind and courteous. But, this image is also exaggerated, which is a common feature of Gothic Novels.

Supply chain management is a process. It involves moving goods from customers to the raw materials stage, then to production, and finally to the customers. The term supply chain management was created in 1982 by a man named Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver explained the process of planning, doing, and controlling activities in a supply chain. He said this process helps meet customers' needs quickly and efficiently.

There are six important parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the base of the supply chain process. The production stage says when, why, where, and how things are made. Managers must know what customers want. They can find out by looking at the market. The market shows what customers need.

Managers study the market and understand what customers want. Then they decide what to make and how much to make. Next, they decide where to make the products and choose a plant for good quality and high volume. They also think about customer satisfaction.

After that, managers plan workloads and take care of equipment. Production is very important in the supply chain process. Every detail matters. If details are not planned, it can cost a lot of time and money.

For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. They have a plan for every part of their business. There is a plan for employee uniforms and receiving shipments. This plan makes the business work smoothly.

Supply is the second key element. It means making decisions about a company's core skills and partnerships. A company may have many divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and skills. Managers decide which division is best for each process. They may also decide to work with other companies to reduce costs.

The reason managers outsource work is to be fast and flexible. Being fast and flexible means giving good quality and low costs.

A sign on a street corner in Burma says that Hitler is living there.

Ellen Page, a famous actress, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a cardboard sign high above her head. The sign has a message written on it in black marker.

Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. A long time ago, a group of military leaders took control of the country. They did not allow people to vote or speak freely. There were many protests in 2007. Many Burmese monks led the protests. The monks wore orange robes. The protests were called the Saffron Revolution.

At first, the government allowed the monks to gather peacefully. But soon, the situation became violent. Many people were hurt or killed. Foreign journalists were arrested and put in prison. One journalist from Japan was killed. The government said 13 people were killed. But a high-ranking military officer said many more people were killed. He said, "Many people have died recently. The number of deaths is in the thousands."

This has happened many times in history. Long ago, some leaders thought they were gods and had complete control over their people. Today, some leaders try to keep people from speaking out against them. A long time ago, the Chinese government stopped a big protest at Tiananmen Square. Many people were killed. The government said 200-300 people were killed. But another group said 2,000-3,000 people were killed.

In another country, Rwanda, a group of people began killing Tutsis and others they did not like. Many people were killed. A long time ago, a man named Hitler led a group that killed many Jews. His group was called the Third Reich.

Duke Ellington was a famous jazz musician. He had a long career. This helped him make great music with his orchestra. He was good at writing music that showed each musician's skill. Ellington wrote music that allowed each musician to play freely. He also wrote music that sounded good together.

Ellington played piano in some of his music. But he was not the only musician. He made sure each musician had a special part in the music. This made the music sound new and exciting. Ellington's music was one of a kind. He was good at writing music that sounded good together.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's music. They say he used the human voice as a musical instrument. This is shown in a song called Creole Love Call. In this song, Ellington uses the voice to add color and texture to the music. He does not use words in this song. He uses the voice like an instrument.

Creole Love Call is a slow song. It has six parts. Each part is different. The first part has a call and response between the voice and the reeds. The voice starts smooth and then gets rough. The second part has a muted trumpet solo. The third part has a clarinet solo with a piano phrase. The fourth part is like the first part. The fifth part is the most exciting part. The reeds do the call and response in a high voice. The brass and rhythm sections make a strong sound. The sixth part is like the first part. But the voice sounds different.

In the last part, the voice makes a growling sound. This is like a special effect. Ellington liked to use the voice in his music to add color and texture. This is one way he was different from other musicians.

In another song called Hot and Bothered, Ellington uses his skill at writing music that sounds good together. He uses a call and response between a muted trumpet and scat singing. This makes a rich and exciting sound. In another song, It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington uses a trombone to introduce the melody. He chooses a musician who is good at playing the trombone.

She felt something missing. This feeling started when she was 14. It continued three years later when she was 17. She thought she wanted a person, not just anything. But she did not like any boy. Some boys liked her, but she did not feel the same. She often thought about this strange feeling.

Her life at home was usually quiet. Her parents were kind and calm. They rarely argued with each other. Her parents also rarely argued with her. They liked her to be independent. She was a happy person and her parents liked her.

But today was not a quiet day. She heard her mother scream in the kitchen. She ran into the room and said, "Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother was on the ground, in pain. She said "Ow" many times. Her daughter helped her mother and said, "I will take you to the hospital." Her mother told her where to pick her up. Her daughter was happy she had taken classes to be strong. She carried her mother to the car and drove.

The hospital was a scary place. It smelled bad and made her worried. But she was not worried, only thinking about her mother. She carried her mother to the doctor and called for help. The doctors came and took care of her mother.

Her mother fell off a little stool while getting a vase from high up.

This study showed that eating like people in the Mediterranean area is good for your heart.  This way of eating is called the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet).  A higher "aMed diet score" means you eat more foods from plants and fish, and less meat and bad fats.  You can also have a little alcohol.

Past studies showed that eating the Med diet can help you live longer and be healthier.  But these studies did not look at how it affects strokes.

This study followed 74,886 women between 38 and 63 years old.  They were part of a bigger study of 121,700 women nurses in 11 US states.  The women answered questions about what they ate for 20 years.  Six times, they filled out a "food frequency questionnaire" to tell us what they ate.  Most of the women kept participating in the study for 20 years.  The food questionnaires were checked for accuracy.  When the women got heart disease or a stroke, the study checked medical records to confirm it. 

The study looked at many things that could affect the results.  The study controlled for age, smoking, weight, hormone use, and exercise.  It also looked at how much the women drank and if they took aspirin.

A computer program was used to see if eating like people in the Mediterranean area helps prevent heart disease and stroke.  The study found that women who ate like this had a lower risk of getting heart disease and stroke.

The study followed the women for 20 years.  In this time, 2391 women got heart disease, 1763 women had a stroke, and 1077 women died from heart disease or stroke.  Women who ate the most like people in the Mediterranean area were less likely to get heart disease and stroke than women who ate the least like them.  The risk was 71% lower.

In 2007, the United States was in big financial trouble. Many people lost their jobs, and the housing market fell. This is still happening today. We must ask: how did this happen and how can we stop it? 

The financial crisis was caused by poor decisions made by leaders in government. They made banks give loans to people who could not pay them back. This happened because the financial system was not ready for it. Two big companies, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, were forced to buy and sell these bad loans. When people did not pay their loans, the banks did not have enough money. This caused big problems for the whole economy.

The start of the financial crisis was in 1999. President Clinton wanted to win a second term in office. He wanted to make more people happy with him. To do this, he made it easier for banks to give loans to people. This made it possible for the financial crisis to happen seven years later.

A journalist named Steven Holmes wrote about the problem in 1999. He said that Fannie Mae was giving loans to people who could not afford them. He also said that this could cause a big problem if the economy slowed down.

Many things worked together to make the financial crisis worse. New types of loans, like adjustable-rate mortgages, were used a lot. This made the economy depend too much on the housing market. People and banks borrowed too much money and were not prepared for a change in the housing market.

The housing market then crashed, and the banks that bought the bad loans were in trouble. The top five investment banks in the US had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007. This is a lot of money. Some banks were sold cheaply, and others had to be regulated closely. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition is a bad thing in writing.  It is when you tell too much about a story.  Sometimes it makes readers bored or angry.  Dr. Merlin gets angry when she reads too much exposition.  It is like a bad devil that tells you to tell everything before you start the good parts.

You know the rule "Show, don't tell."  Dr. Merlin still forgets this rule and writes long parts with nothing happening.  Exposition is when you tell the readers what happened.  In films, one character tells another a lot of information.  In writing, the author does the telling.

Let's look at an example.  A story says a woman meets a man, they get married, and he dies.  You don't want to read two pages about this.  You want to see how the man loves the woman and how she feels about him.  This makes you care about them and what happens to them.  You would want to know more about the man's character.  How does he talk and act?  How does the woman feel about him?  This helps you understand the story better.

As a writer, you need to add meat to the story.  You can't just say "They met, they married, he died."  You need to make it interesting.  Sometimes it is hard to do this.  But you must try.  For example, you are introducing a new character.  You know he used to be in the Air Force and now he works at a gas station.  You also know he is married, likes fishing and has a secret dream.  You don't need to tell all this at once.  You can show it through his actions and words.

I watched two news programs on TV from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was live on NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who hurt his wife very badly. He is named Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture, and he looked very bad. They only talked about this story for two minutes because it was still happening. They said he hurt his wife many times and was arrested. I think they gave it enough time.

The second story was about a young man, Travis Buyers, 18, who was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was hurt badly, but no one knew who shot him. The police were investigating. This story was short. I think it might be because the victim was a black man. I have noticed before that when minorities are hurt, the news does not talk about it as much. If a white person is hurt, the news talks about it a lot.

The next story was about a hole in a helicopter. They said it was shot by a bullet from a small rifle. The police want you to call if you know who did it. They are offering a five-thousand-dollar reward.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. They said it would be hot, but then it would rain. They wanted to make you stay tuned to the news to find out more.

They also told a story about a store robbery on Clime Road in Columbus. A black man, who was wearing a hood, robbed the store. They talked about how dark he was, which seemed unusual.

Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez from Texas. He was a big drug dealer. He was sent to prison for 25 years for selling marijuana. They also said he was a Hispanic man, but that was not important to the story.

There is a strong connection between brothers. This connection is very strong and hard to break. It includes many feelings like love, pride, jealousy, and anger. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. When they look at their brother, they see themselves. In bad situations, the true nature of this connection shows itself. It can be good or bad. When we understand these feelings, we must face the bad things that come with them. We see ourselves in our brother. We see our true character in our actions and the results of those actions.

In "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers explore this idea. They go on a journey to the countryside. The author describes the land very well. Bitter disappointment and strong pride come together in a big scene. Only one brother survives. The story shows the readers how the brother with the disability feels through his actions and talks.

The brother's actions are all because of one main feeling: pride. From the start, the brother wants a brother who can do all the things he can do. He wants a brother to play with and to be friends with. But the little brother cannot do these things. He is very sick and cannot play like other children. The big brother is very angry and disappointed. He even thinks about hurting his brother. But when the little brother smiles, he feels happy. This shows that the big brother loves his brother.

The human brain is a very complex system. It helps us think and learn. As technology gets better, we use better words to describe the brain. In the past, we compared it to a flat piece of wax, then a piece of paper, and then a book. Now, we compare it to a computer.

The brain gets information from our senses. These senses are like special helpers that take in things like touch, heat, sound, and light. They turn these things into special signals. The brain then changes these signals many times. This makes it easier to understand the information.

When we look at something, the brain works in two ways. One way is from the bottom up. This means it takes small pieces of information and makes them into bigger pieces. For example, when we look at a black box on white paper, the brain uses small pieces of information like color and shape to decide that it is a box. The other way is from the top down. This means it uses what we already know to understand the information. This helps us learn things faster.

The brain has a filter that decides what is important and what we should pay attention to. This is like a choice. We don't notice small things like the blades of grass when we look at our shoes. But when we hear our name in a loud place, we listen carefully.

The brain has many steps to process information. It stores what we learn in different kinds of memory. There are three main kinds: sensory, working, and long-term memory. First, the brain encodes the information. This means it changes the information into a way that the brain can understand. For example, if we hear a word, the brain can change it into how it sounds, how it looks, or what it means.

The brain also has to keep the information we learn. It does this by sending a special signal to the right neurons. Some studies on animals show that this signal helps us remember things for a short time. We keep long-term memories in the structure of special proteins.

There are many ways to understand how the brain organizes what we know. Some are based on how people remember things, others are based on computers, and others are based on how the brain works. One idea is that the brain is like a web. Each idea is a node, and the nodes are connected to each other if they are related. For example, the word "chair" might be connected to "table," which is connected to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley writes about a bad future in the book Brave New World. He is worried about how technology and a system called capitalism can hurt people. In this world, people put the community first and are taught to be happy all the time. But, the people are really just being controlled. They do not have a choice.

The people in this world are like pawns in a game. They are told what to think and believe. A person in charge, called the World Controller, makes all the decisions. 

If we look at the book from a certain point of view called Marxist theory, we can see that Huxley does not like the way people are treated. He uses special words from this theory to show how he feels. For example, he talks about how people are the same and how they are changed into what they are meant to be.

Huxley also criticizes capitalism. He says that people do not know the truth about how the system works. They are too busy thinking about their own happiness. The people in control make sure the common people do not know about the real problems. They control the people through a special sleep teaching method called hypnopædia. This makes people want to buy and spend money all the time.

The lower classes do not know they are being controlled. They do what they are told. The people in charge use a system called hegemony to control them. This means that one group of people has power over all the others. The upper classes know this, but they do not do anything to stop it. Only a few characters in the book, like Bernard, try to understand what is happening.

The people in Brave New World do not have real relationships. They do not know each other deeply. Huxley may be saying that technology and capitalism take away people's freedom to make choices and express themselves. The people in this world do not love each other or feel strong emotions. They only talk about physical things, like how someone looks.

The people in this world are happy to be where they are in the system. This shows how capitalism can make people obey and not question the system. This is what Marxist theory says about the people who work but do not have power.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years now. Getting around campus can be hard for many people. My first year, I lived in a dorm room in East Halls, which is far from the center of campus. To go to class in the Willard building, I had to walk a long way. It took up to 25 minutes to walk, especially when the weather is bad. Some time ago, the area near East Halls was empty land. The school built new sports fields and big buildings there. It is now full of apartments. As the campus grows, it is harder to get from one place to another. The best way to solve this problem is to use a bicycle. But just having a bike is not enough. Students and the school need to make sure the campus is safe for bicyclists.

I talked to a friend who started riding a bike again. He said it is a great way to travel. He said it was not cool to ride a bike for a few years, but now it is the best way to get around. Riding a bike is good for your body and it is fast. You can go 30 miles or more with just eating a simple meal and exercising a little. I live off campus now, which is far from the center of campus. I decided to buy a bike and it was the best decision I made this year. It takes 25 minutes to walk to my class in Thomas building. But if I ride my bike, it takes only 5 minutes. I have to be careful because Pollock Road is not always easy to ride on.

Walking is also good, but I am too busy. If I did not have my bike, I would have to walk to class every day. It would take 30-40 minutes extra every day. That is two and a half hours every week. I do not have time for that.

original_texts:
Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.  Though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether stated benefits, like diversification, do indeed exist, and the extent to which they exist.  For the purposes of this effort, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of a owning a single ETF come close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also whether or not there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal sharp ratio or return.
	In order to evaluate the ETF, it would become rather unwieldy to include every holding, therefore we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF.  Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

	In order to gain an estimation of how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to  calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolioâ€™s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings.  The calculations of Beta and return are included in the below chart.

From the above chart it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is .12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta.  However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.
	In order to evaluate whether or not these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. 
Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see, however, how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to combat that dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change during the course of the project. If the prizes, however, were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than adequate at the outset of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participating and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the borders of the stage. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of the trick films; most of them focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in substance and in name an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been disparaged, praised, accused of having no real depth, and lauded for the 'terrible sublime' aspect it seemed to evoke (Burke).
